<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38221b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38221b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38221b"> 221(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Session of Snakes</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I will take from The Nights, as a specimen of the true Persian romance, &ldquo;The Queen of the Serpents&rdquo; (vol. v. 298), the subject of Lane&apos;s Carlylean denunciation. The first gorgeous picture is the <mark>Session of the Snakes</mark> which, like their Indian congeners the N&aacute;ga kings and queens, have human heads and reptile bodies, an Egyptian myth that engendered the &ldquo;old serpent&rdquo; of Genesis. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 129</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
